\section*{INTRODUCTION}

Plant diseases are complex and caused by a diverse array of pathogen types, including fungi, viruses, bacteria, oomycetes, nematodes, phytoplasmas, and other parasitic plants (Strange \& Scott, 2005). Among them, fungal pathogens are the most common causes of emerging plant diseases
(Anderson et al., 2004) and infection can have catastrophic consequences for their hosts and people (Anagnostakis, 1987; Bruns, 2017; McCook \& Vandermeer, 2015).

Increased rates of pathogen emergence (Bebber et al., 2014) require explanation, leading to a growing body of research on factors influencing host shifts and host range expansions. While the full suite of factors that

