\section*{RESULTS}

We reconstructed the Botryosphaeriaceae phylogeny (Figure 1 and Appendix S1: Figure S1) using maximum likelihood on a matrix of 27,617 sequences for ITS, tub2, tef, LSU, and/or rpb2, summarized at the species level. While we believe our reconstruction is the most comprehensive yet produced for Botryosphaeriaceae, to maximize resolution, we excluded isolates with fewer than three genes sequenced, and our tree therefore omits some species from the family (including the monotypic genus Botryobambusa (Dissanayake et al., 2021) and the duotypic Mucoharknessia). Nonetheless, our reconstruction includes 193 species ( $\sim 80 \%$ of the total number of species currently recognized within the family; Batista et al., 2021 v 3.0 ) and 19 of the 21 recognized genera (Yang, Groenewald, et al., 2017; Zhang, Groenewald, et al., 2021), following recent taxonomic revisions where possible (see, e.g., Yang, Groenewald, et al., 2017; Zhang, Groenewald, et al., 2021). Genera with the highest number of species include Botryosphaeria (12), Diplodia (25), Dothiorella (34), Lasiodiplodia (43), and Neofusicoccum (43) (Appendix S1: Figures S2-S6).

\section*{Evolutionary relatedness strongly informs Botryosphaeriaceae-plant host associations}

Variation in host breadth may be explained by phylogenetic constraints of hosts, the fungi, or both. The importance of pathogen and host evolutionary histories in structuring host-pathogen associations is revealed by the mapping of the phylogeny of plant hosts onto the phylogeny of Botryosphaeriaceae fungi (Figure 2a). Host plants were, on average, associated with $4.458 \pm 4.867$ fungal taxa (mean $\pm \mathrm{SD} ; \mathrm{SE}=0.20$ ), with V. vinifera (grapes; 56 Botryosphaeriaceae species), Eucalyptus spp. (43), M. indica (mangos; 32), and Citrus spp. (28) having the
highest diversity of recorded Botryosphaeriaceae associations (Figure 2a,c, bottom). Fungal species with the highest reported host range were M. phaseolina (604 host species), Lasiodiplodia theobromae (548), Botryosphaeria dothidea (529), N. parvum (295), and Diplodia seriata (130) (Figure 2a,c, top), considered hyper-generalists, capable of infecting hundreds of hosts. The average host use by Botryosphaeriaceae was $28.669 \pm 86.670$ plant species (mean $\pm \mathrm{SD} ; \mathrm{SE}=7.432$ ), suggesting a predominance of generalists over specialists.

We first examined the evidence for phylogenetic structure in Botryosphaeriaceae-host plant associations using the SES of the mean phylogenetic pairwise distance (ses.MPD) between Botryosphaeriaceae species summarized across each plant host, and between plant hosts summarized across each fungal species (Figure 2b). We found phylogenetic clustering ( $z$ score $<0$ ) both among hosts and fungi (one-sample $t$ test to evaluate statistical deviation from zero, $t=-7.088$, $\mathrm{df}=597$, and $t=$ -6.222 , df $=132$, for host and fungi, respectively, both $p<0.001$ ), supporting phylogenetic conservatism in host use among fungal pathogens and fungal susceptibility among plant hosts: Botryosphaeriaceae fungi tend to infect plant hosts more closely related than expected by chance, and plants tend to be infected by more closely related Botryosphaeriaceae than expected by chance. The strength of clustering measured on the host phylogeny was significantly different from the strength of clustering measured on the fungal phylogeny (mean $z$ score $=$ -0.865 vs. -0.488 , measured on the host and fungal phylogeny, respectively, Welch two-sample $t$ test $t=-2.432$, $\mathrm{df}=201.92, p<0.05$ ), with a trend for tighter phylogenetic clustering of the hosts associated with individual Botryosphaeriaceae than observed among the fungal species able to colonize each plant host. However, we observe variation in both the strength and sign of clustering among hyper-generalists (Figure 2d). For example, $M$. phaseolina has a $z$ score of 1.181, indicating that its hosts tend to be more evenly dispersed across the host phylogeny, whereas B. dothidea has a $z$ score of -0.707 , indicating that its hosts are more clustered on the host phylogeny.

