\section*{Specialism versus generalism}

Visual assessment of fungal host breadth relative to their phylogenetic relationship did not suggest any obvious structure. Generalist Botryosphaeriaceae do not appear to be clustered in one clade but are rather dispersed across the fungal phylogeny. We quantified the phylogenetic signal in the number of reported plant hosts across the Botryosphaeriaceae phylogeny using Blomberg's $K$ (Blomberg et al., 2003). Matching to observations, we found no statistically significant signal ( $K=0.22, p>0.05$ ).

While we most commonly define generalist and specialist fungi by their number of reported hosts, as above, some fungi might be associated with a high total number of hosts but span only a narrow breadth of the host phylogeny if hosts are closely related, and other fungi might infect only a few hosts, but those hosts might be distantly related. We, therefore, evaluated the relationship between host richness and host PDiv (Figure 2c, top) and repeat this for fungal richness on plant hosts with PDiv measured on the fungal phylogeny (Figure 2c, bottom). We show that taxon richness strongly correlates with PDiv, and thus, hosts or fungi with a greater number of associations span a greater breadth of the fungal and plant phylogeny, respectively. However, we note that hyper-generalist fungi such as B. dothidea, L. theobromae, M. phaseolina, and N. parvum tend to be outliers, infecting plants that are more or less closely related than the overall trend (Figure 2c, top).

\section*{Specialists tend to transition toward generalism}

If generalism were a transitionary state, we might expect a greater frequency of generalism among younger fungal taxa. However, we found no significant correlation between host breadth and taxon age ( $t$ value $=-1.017$, $F$-statistic $=1.034$ on 1 and $194 \mathrm{df}, p>0.05$ from pgls). Moreover, we observed an overall greater number of generalists ( 134 species) than specialists ( 62 species) (Figure 3a). Here, we defined generalists as fungi with $>2$ hosts, but we would have to relax the definition of specialism to encompass taxa with up to 4 hosts before we would return a different ratio of specialists and generalists across the family.

We further explored the evolutionary trajectory between specialism and generalism by examining the transition rates between them, assuming discrete states. Using maximum
likelihood, we found that the transition rate from specialist to generalist was almost twice as likely as the shift from generalist to specialist $\left(2.06 \times 10^{-1}\right.$ and $9.41 \times 10^{-2}$, respectively; Figure 3b).

One explanation for an apparent greater transition rate toward generalism might be a higher extinction rate of specialist fungi (Farrell et al., 2021); thus, some evolutionary transitions toward a narrower set of hosts could go unobserved (Igic et al., 2004). We therefore evaluated the relationship between transition rates and speciation and extinction rates using the BiSSE (Fitzjohn, 2012; Maddison et al., 2007). While we detected a higher extinction rate for specialists ( $\mu=1.5 \times 10^{7}$ ) than for generalists ( $\mu=3.0 \times 10^{8}$ ), comparisons with a null in which we enforced equal extinction rates for both specialists and generalists did not indicate statistical support for the two-rate model ( $\chi^{2}=3.27 \times 10^{-5}, \quad p>0.05$, from ANOVA of the two-rate model vs. the equal rate model), and the model in which transitions to generalism were more frequent was again preferred.

Because host generalism can be quantified across a continuous spectrum, we extended our analysis to consider transitions between hierarchical levels of generalism and specialism: (1) 1-2 hosts-specialists, (2) $3-4$ hosts, (3) $5-6$ hosts, (4) $7-8$ hosts, (5) $9-10$ hosts, (6) $11-15$ hosts, (7) $16-20$ hosts, (8) $21-50$ hosts, (9) 51-100 hosts, and (10) $100+$ hosts-hyper-generalists. We find that transition rates from level (1) (1-2 hosts) to (3) (5-6 hosts), and from level (4) to (6) were at least one order of magnitude higher than other transitions increasing host breadth (Figure 3c). Similarly, transitions decreasing the number of hosts were also higher from level (6) to (4) and from (3) to (2) than transitions between these groupings. Surprisingly, transitions from highly specialist levels (1) and (2) to broad generalism (9) were also relatively frequent.

