\section*{DISCUSSION}

Fungi are among the most common and economically important pathogens causing emerging infectious diseases in plants (Anderson et al., 2004). However, the factors shaping fungal-plant associations and driving the emergence of pathogenic fungi in novel hosts are still not well understood. We examined patterns of host associations in the Botryosphaeriaceae, a fungal family containing many highly virulent pathogens of plants. Exploring pathogen and host phylogenies, we found strong phylogenetic conservatism in fungal-plant interactions across both. We also show that host generalism is more common than specialism in the Botryosphaeriaceae and that the evolutionary transition rate from specialism to generalism is higher than the reverse pathway. We additionally identify surprisingly frequent transitions from specialism to hyper-generalism. We
suggest that, in addition to phylogenetic constraints to plant-fungal associations, geographical factors likely influence the realized host breadth of fungi by limiting the plant hosts they are exposed to. We show a greater host range in fungi with plant hosts used by humans. We propose that the human movement of plants has allowed some associated fungi to escape ecological and evolutionary constraints on host range and may explain the emergence of hyper-generalist pathogens in this family.

\section*{The Botryosphaeriaceae phylogeny}

The Botryosphaeriaceae fungal family contains a wide and diverse group of species, many of them known for their damaging effects on plant health. However, the classification of this fungal taxon has been a challenge since its first description in 1918 (Theissen \& Sydow, 1918), with multiple efforts worldwide to resolve the Botryosphaeriaceae taxonomy (Burgess et al., 2019; Crous et al., 2006; Phillips et al., 2013; Schoch et al., 2006; Slippers et al., 2004; Wingfield et al., 2012). The presence of cryptic species led to the questioning of the taxonomic status of several lineages (Pavlic et al., 2009). Following phylogenetic analyses with new and more sensitive molecular tools, several species have been synonymized in the last few years (Yang, Groenewald, et al., 2017; Zhang, Groenewald, et al., 2021), and multigene phylogenies and whole-genome sequencing have provided additional information on evolutionary relationships (Garcia et al., 2021; Yu et al., 2022). Here, we reconstruct a comprehensive phylogeny of the Botryosphaeriaceae, providing new insights into their evolutionary history, and use it to explore host-pathogen associations.

