\section*{Phylogenetic signal in host-fungal associations}

A considerable amount of research has been centered on the phylogenetic conservatism of host use by pests but has largely ignored the evolutionary history of those pests, mainly because we generally have a better
knowledge of plant phylogenies than the phylogenies of pests or pathogens (Gougherty \& Davies, 2021; Smith \& Brown, 2018). However, considering both host and pest phylogenies can give us a deeper understanding of their associations (Gougherty \& Davies, 2021; Morris \& Moury, 2019). We first examined the strength of phylogenetic conservatism across pathogen and host phylogenies independently to assess the importance of both sides of the interaction. We found strong clustering of pathogenic taxa associated with each host when quantified on the fungal phylogeny (Plant hosts, Figure 2c), and also strong clustering of plant hosts associated with each fungus when quantified on the plant phylogeny (Fungi, Figure 2c). Pathogen-host interactions frequently reflect evolutionary conservatism of traits such that related plant hosts tend to harbor similar pathogen species, and related pathogens tend to attack similar plant hosts (Gilbert \& Webb, 2007; Morris \& Moury, 2019). Our results broadly confirm this expectation: Fungi within Botryosphaeriaceae are typically restricted to closely related plants, and closely related Botryosphaeriaceae more frequently colonize the same hosts, which usually provide similar resources and defense strategies (Nylin et al., 2018).

While there is evidence for phylogenetic constraints across both phylogenies, we found a trend for stronger clustering of the plants used by Botryosphaeriaceae than for clustering of Botryosphaeriaceae on their plant hosts, suggesting a greater influence of the host phylogeny in determining their interaction. Results from the co-phylogenetic method proposed by Krasnov et al. (2012) were broadly consistent-closely related Botryosphaeriaceae/plant hosts
are more likely to co-occur in the same module than distantly related Botryosphaeriaceae/plant hosts. However, clusters of host-fungal associations within modules were structured by both host and pathogen phylogenies equally. Our results emphasize the importance of considering both phylogenetic dimensions-host and pathogen-to fully understand their associations.

Co-diversification provides one mechanism that can drive patterns of phylogenetic conservatism in species associations across host and pathogen phylogenies, where the divergence of a pathogen or pest lineage is the result of the divergence of its host lineage (Charleston \& Robertson, 2002). Using the co-phylogenetic method ParaFitGlobal, proposed by Legendre et al. (2002), we found that the phylogenetic structure in host-pest associations was consistent with a model of codivergence between Botryosphaeriaceae and their hosts. Co-diversification between animal parasites and their hosts has been widely reported (Alcala et al., 2017; Hadfield et al., 2014; Pfenning-Butterworth, Botero-Cañola, \& Cressler, 2021), but evidence in fungal plant pathogens is sparse (see example in Peterson et al., 2010). However, phylogenetically constrained host-shifts can give rise to similar patterns (Charleston \& Robertson, 2002; Mazel et al., 2018). Given the evolutionary depth of the pathogen phylogeny relative to the host phylogeny (seed plants-angiosperms and gymnosperms-date to around 246.6 Mya, while Botryosphaeriaceae date to 69.9 Mya; Morris et al., 2018; Rathnayaka et al., 2023), we suggest that a model of host switching is more likely to explain the patterns of pathogen-host associations we observe across the Botryosphaeriaceae.

While most fungi have a phylogenetically conserved host range, hyper-generalists such as B. dothidea, L. theobromae, M. phaseolina, and N. parvum, with over 10 times the number of known hosts than the Botryosphaeriaceae average, seem to be exceptions. The existence of generalists able to infect distantly related hosts has been described as the "parasite paradox" (Agosta et al., 2010). The paradox arises from the observation that pathogens and parasites tend to be resource specialists, leading to selection for constrained host ranges, and yet, jumps to unrelated hosts are common and observable in ecological time (Agosta et al., 2010). These hyper-generalist taxa within Botryosphaeriaceae thus further support the host-switching hypothesis over codivergence. Previous research suggested that "ecological fitting" could be one mechanism initializing host-switching, helping to resolve the parasite paradox (Agosta et al., 2010; Araujo et al., 2015). Originally proposed by Daniel Janzen (1985), the concept suggests that species can establish functional ecological associations without the need for long evolutionary histories, as they
can "fit" into new environments through pre-existing traits and phenotypic flexibility.

Ecological fitting of Botryosphaeriaceae hyper-generalist species in new environments could have allowed the quick emergence of new fungal-plant interactions through both intrinsic factors, for example, phenotypic plasticity and weak phylogenetic conservatism (Agosta et al., 2010; Agosta \& Klemens, 2008; Becerra, 1997; Blanco et al., 2018), and external factors, such as changes in biogeographical distribution due to, for example, release from dispersal limitations. Despite the finding of generally strong phylogenetic conservatism in host use, we show a surprising variation in host breadth among closely related Botryosphaeriaceae species (Figure 2), suggesting that heritable fungal traits do not easily explain the number of hosts each Botryosphaeriaceae infects. Host range across the Botryosphaeriaceae, therefore, appears to be an evolutionarily malleable trait with multiple evolutionary independent shifts toward wider and (sometimes) narrower host breadth across the family.

\section*{Transitions between specialism and generalism}

The evolution of host breadth has been an important focus of study in ecology and evolution over the past few decades (Futuyma \& Moreno, 1988; Janz \& Nylin, 2008; Visher \& Boots, 2020). The presence of specialist and generalist pathogens has been predominantly explained in the literature by the cost of generalism, which allows specialists to outcompete generalists in some contexts (MacArthur, 1984; Visher \& Boots, 2020). It has also been suggested that there is a general evolutionary tendency toward specialism based on the assumed trade-off between host resource use efficiency and generalism, where "a jack of all trades is a master of none" (Futuyma \& Moreno, 1988). While generalist pathogens are sometimes observed, it is suggested that there is typically a strong trend toward respecialization (Janz \& Nylin, 2008; Nylin et al., 2018), and specialists usually outnumber generalists (Sriswasdi et al., 2017; Xu et al., 2022). In previous work (Silva-Valderrama, Úrbez-Torres, \& Davies, 2024), we found that most Botryosphaeriaceae had narrow host ranges. Nonetheless, single-host specialists were infrequent, and as our sampling of hosts is almost certainly incomplete, we are likely even further biased to overestimating the number of specialists. It is not immediately clear why Botryosphaeriaceae should differ from other host-parasite systems in having a greater frequency of multihost pathogens.

If generalism were a transient state, as previously proposed, we might predict that generalists would be observed more frequently among younger taxa in the tree
(Nylin et al., 2018), because older taxa would have had more time to evolve toward specialism. However, we found no relation between Botryosphaeriaceae age and host breadth. Moreover, we find no evidence that evolutionary transitions from generalism to specialism are more frequent than the reverse; rather, we found the opposite to be true. The transition rate from specialists to generalists was almost twice as likely as the transition rates from generalism to specialism (Figure 3b).

Our results contrast with some previous findings across other taxa; for example, Sriswasdi et al. (2017) reported that the transition rate from environmental-generalist bacteria toward specialism was three fold faster than the reverse. Likewise, Padfield et al. (2024) reported that transition rates away from generalist states were five times higher than all rates toward it combined. It is possible that threats to plant diversity over the past decades (Corlett, 2016) have tended to increasingly favor generalists, as once common plant hosts become rarer, imposing pressure on parasites to either shift niche preferences or expand their diet breadth (Futuyma \& Moreno, 1988). It is also possible that we underestimated transitions from generalism to specialism; for example, if specialist fungi have higher extinction rates, we might miss transitions in now extinct taxa (Fitzjohn, 2012; Maddison et al., 2007). However, we did not find any evidence suggesting significantly higher extinction in specialists versus generalists, and when fit in a joint model, transition rates from specialism to generalism were still higher than the reverse.

We recognize that the binary classification of specialism and generalism we assume above might be too rigid. We, therefore, explored intermediate thresholds of generalism and specialism and found that transition rates between fungi with one or two hosts were broadly symmetrical, as were transitions between fungi with seven or eight hosts (Figure 3c). These transitions might be a behavioral and temporal response to competition, generating a dynamic balance between gaining and losing hosts. However, perhaps a more likely explanation is that uncertainty in true host breadth due to data gaps does not allow us to accurately distinguish between, for example, true single-host specialists and specialists found in two plant hosts. Thus, apparent transitions between single-host specialists and two-host specialists in our data might simply reflect sampling bias, explaining why they appear to be so frequent.

The blurred threshold between specialists and generalists could also be masking other patterns. For example, phenotypic plasticity can allow generalists to persist in alternative environments through ecological fitting, where selection might favor subsequent adaptation to a novel host (Mason, 2016). However, such hosts are often considered to be deviations rather than indicative of
transitions toward increasing generalism (Nylin et al., 2018). To distinguish between true hosts versus spillover or transient hosts, other factors should be considered, such as the virulence of the fungi, which might be related to resource use efficiency and fungal adaptation to a given host. Future studies linking host breadth and virulence could, therefore, help us to better understand the boundary between generalists and specialists.

Host breadth is not a static property. The expansion of increment of host breadth via formation of novel species association through host-switching and ecological fitting is not an endpoint (Agosta \& Klemens, 2008). The increasing transition of Botryosphaeriaceae fungi toward generalism could also be indicative of an expansion phase within the clade (Agosta \& Klemens, 2008; Janzen, 1985), a product of their current broadening geographical extent and, therefore, part of a broader host-breadth cycle. The oscillation hypothesis (Janz \& Nylin, 2008) links the diversity of pathogens to oscillations in their host plant range. Pathogens may, therefore, alternate between broadening their host breadth and specializing in fewer plant species over evolutionary time. The presence of hyper-generalists might then be a transient phase fueled by increasing opportunities of new interactions and ecological fitting but could, in time, give rise to a specialization phase in which fungi evolve to specialize on their new hosts. Our findings regarding the age of generalists and specialists and evidence for transitions both form and to increased generalism could be consistent with this hypothesis, with different taxa within Botryosphaeriaceae in different phases.

Strikingly, we observed surprisingly high transition rates from specialists (one to two hosts) to hyper-generalists, with over 100 plant-host species (Figure 3c). Such differences in host richness are unlikely to be explained by sampling bias alone, and we suggest that these large shifts in host breadth may be a result of geographical range expansion through the anthropological movement of plant and fungal species worldwide. If this is the case, then we could speculate that the vertiginous increase in host breadth of these hyper-generalists will eventually be limited by world geography. Novel interactions within introduced regions might then give rise to new fungal specialists, reinitiating the cycle.

\section*{Anthropogenic influence on Botryosphaeriaceae host breadth}

The introduction of plant species into new geographical locations has not only allowed native pathogens to interact with these introduced plants but has also provided an opportunity for spillover of pathogens of the introduced plants to the native plant community. In the past century,
the plantation area of agriculturally important species, including V. vinifera (World Wine Production Outlook OIV First Estimates, 2022), Eucalyptus spp. (Burgess \& Wingfield, 2017; Iglesias-Trabado \& Wilstermann, 2008), and M. indica (Liu et al., 2023), has expanded dramatically. Eucalyptus spp., for example, are some of the most widely planted tree species in the world, with forestry plantations in over 95 countries (Zhang \& Wang, 2021). Most species are endemic to Australia (Yost et al., 2021), but many have been moved around the globe to produce pulp, paper, and wood, and pathogens have moved with them. Several fungi of the genus Teratosphaeria have likely been co-introduced with their Eucalyptus hosts (Burgess \& Wingfield, 2017), and native pathogens, such as Puccinia psidii (Glen et al., 2007) and Cryphonectria spp., have emerged on introduced Eucalyptus (Burgess \& Wingfield, 2017; Wingfield, 2003). Fungi within Botryosphaeriaceae that are associated with Eucalyptus have thus been exposed to a large number of potential hosts and opportunities for host range expansion.

We show that generalist Botryosphaeriaceae are disproportionately associated with economically important crops such as Eucalyptus spp., M. indica, and V. vinifera (Figure 4), and that fungi associated with plant hosts of human use have, on average, greater host ranges than fungi associated with plant hosts not used by humans. The anthropogenic movement of crops and domesticated plants has likely allowed some Botryosphaeriaceae to overcome the natural geographical limitations to their host distributions. In addition, crop management practices could have favored higher diversity of fungal species in agricultural plants. For example, increased pathogen susceptibility could result from trade-offs in plant breeding that selects for traits that favor higher productivity (Silva-Valderrama, Úrbez-Torres, \& Davies, 2024), and because the spread rate of a pathogen is proportional to the density of susceptible hosts (Burdon \& Chilvers, 2003; Gilbert \& Webb, 2007), the dense planting of crops in monocultures likely further amplifies the ecological opportunity for plant-pathogen interactions. Greater investment in research of economically important crops can, however, generate a sampling bias, leading us to artifactually record a higher number of pathogens in these hosts (Gramaje et al., 2018; Jayawardena et al., 2018; Silva-Valderrama, Úrbez-Torres, \& Davies, 2024). Nonetheless, we were able to show that the frequency of economically important crops among the hosts of fungi with wide host breadth was significantly greater than expected by chance.

We suggest that the extreme relaxation of dispersal limitation through human movement of plant species might provide the explanation for the recent and rapid expansion of Botryosphaeriaceae host breadth. Araujo
et al. (2015) identify the two critical steps necessary for new interactions to establish as (i) opportunity, where potential associates must coexist in time and space; and (ii) compatibility, where the resources for colonization, spread, and persistence are present. The opportunity for an increased number of interactions provided by the anthropogenic movement of plant species, and an ability to maintain fitness in a novel host and environment-ecological fitting (Agosta \& Klemens, 2008)-provided by phenotypic plasticity and relaxed phylogenetic niche conservatism may have acted together to promote the emergence of Botryosphaeriaceae hyper-generalists that we see nowadays.

\section*{CONCLUSION}

Fungi within the Botryosphaeriaceae include single-host specialists and hyper-generalists found on $>100$ plant species, but the majority of species might be classified as moderate generalists. We show evidence of phylogenetic conservatism in fungal-plant interaction, where both pathogen and plant phylogenies inform their association. Individual fungi, therefore, tend to infect closely related plant hosts, and a given plant host is likely to be susceptible to infection from closely related fungal parasites. However, we found that single-host specialists are rare within the Botryosphaeriaceae and that there is a higher rate of evolutionary transitions toward generalism than to specialism, contrary to theory suggesting that generalism is a transient state. We suggest that biogeographical factors and the anthropological movement of economically important crop species around the globe might be important in explaining the large variation in host breadth of fungi within the family and the presence of hyper-generalists. Botryosphaeriaceae species associated with widely planted crops, such as Eucalyptus, V. vinifera, and M. indica, have had greater opportunity to spill over onto novel hosts and expand their host range. Furthermore, the dense planting of agricultural crops, often in monoculture, likely facilitated spillover of native pathogens onto these introduced species. Understanding the factors that determine pathogen host range can aid in predicting the risk of emerging Botryosphaeriaceae fungi, helping to inform efficient regulatory policies in international trade in plant and plant-derived products, and influence the design of agricultural systems to reduce the host breadth expansion and emergence of pathogenic fungi.

